'''David Gaider''' is a writer and a [[Star Wars video games|video game]] designer,<ref name="LinkedIn" /> and was part of the design team of ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]''<ref name="KOTOR">''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]''</ref>. He worked for [[BioWare]] from [[1999]] to [[2016]],<ref name="LinkedIn" /> and he is also known to be the Lead Writer for the [[Wikipedia:Dragon Age|''Dragon Age'' series]].<ref name="DA">{{WebCite|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development-news/the-man-who-built-thedas-interview-with-david-gaider|text=The man who built Thedas: Interview with David Gaider|date=2016-06-07|work=[[Wikipedia:MCV/Develop|MCV/Develop]]|archivedate=20210109174813}}</ref>

On ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]'', Gaider worked as a designer<ref name="KOTOR" /> and writer. He is responsible for [[HK-47]], [[Carth Onasi]], [[Korriban/Legends|Korriban]] (and the [[Code of the Sith/Legends|Code of the Sith]]), [[Jolee Bindo]], and part of [[Bastila Shan]].<ref name="Twitter1">{{Twitter|davidgaider|status/1389640959072215040|David Gaider|quote=I wrote Carth, HK-47, the Sith planet Korriban (and the Code of the Sith!), a lot of Bastila... [...] Every time I list the things I wrote on KotOR, I forget about Jolee Bindo.|archivedate=20210505072220}}</ref> He admitted that, being mostly a fantasy writer, the game was difficult for him to work on at first. His "writer's block" disappeared after [[James Ohlen]] offered a different perspective on ''[[Star Wars]]'', describing it not as a sci-fi world, but as a fantasy setting. Thus Gaider started taking more pleasure in his work.<ref name="Twitter2">{{Twitter|davidgaider|status/1389640959072215040|David Gaider|quote=I had an incredibly hard time working on Knights of the Old Republic, at first. I'd written fantasy for so long, I couldn't wrap my head around sci-fi. When James came to talk to me about my obvious difficulties, I remember bursting into tears. I didn't know how to write this.<br />"Thing is," James advised me, "Star War IS fantasy. It has wizards and magic and monsters and heroes. It just has a science-fiction setting. If you stop thinking of it as sci-fi and write it exactly as you did fantasy, you'll be OK."<br />And... that worked. The writer's block I was having just ended, and not only was I speeding along again I was having FUN. There were fantasy themes here I could explore, and issues of morality we really never addressed before.|archivedate=20210505072220}}</ref>

Though it was not stated in the game, Gaiden named Onasi's [[Death/Legends|deceased]] [[Marriage/Legends|wife]] "[[Morgana Onasi|Morgana]]."<ref name="SWForums">{{WebCite|url=http://swforums.bioware.com/viewtopic.html?topic=505520&forum=76|text=I have a problem/question.|work=BioWare's KotOR forums|archivedate=20090314070518}}</ref>

